<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-638-752  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 638 752.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics Weekly  May 23 1990 n1509 p10(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Government moves to scare computer hackers. (Computer Misuse Bill)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Martin, Diana.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The British House of Commons passes special legislation that willallow the prosecution of computer hackers.andP;  The House of Lords isexpected to rubberstamp the bill.andP;  The bill outlines threepossible offenses: unauthorized access to data or programs, fraudor blackmail, and unauthorized modification of data or programs.andO;Users' reactions have been mixed, with some people fearing thatthe bill is too weak and others saying it will be difficult toenforce.andP;  Computer crimes are hard to detect.andP;  Spokespersons forthe Computer Threat Research Association and the British ComputerSociety insist that the bill is simply not powerful enough.andP;  Bothgroups, however, support the bill as a step in the rightdirection.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United KingdomLegislationComputer CrimesUser GroupsComputer HackersComputer Industry.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>